To find the union of sets A and B, we combine all the elements from both sets without repeating any elements. So, the union of sets A and B is:

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}

Now, we need to show that set A is a subset of the union of sets A and B. A set A is a subset of another set B (denoted as A ⊆ B) if every element of A is also an element of B. In this case, we have:

A = {1, 3, 5}
A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}

Since every element of set A (1, 3, and 5) is also an element of the union A ∪ B, we can say that A ⊆ (A ∪ B).

Next, we need to show that set B is a subset of the union of sets A and B. Similarly, we have:

B = {2, 4, 6}
A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}

Since every element of set B (2, 4, and 6) is also an element of the union A ∪ B, we can say that B ⊆ (A ∪ B).

In conclusion, we have found the union of sets A and B, and we have shown that both set A and set B are subsets of the union of sets A and B.
